2️⃣ Manual Mapping (Old Way 😓)

Before tools like MapStruct, developers converted Entity → DTO manually by writing setter/getter code themselves.

This is called manual mapping.

✅ Example Setup
Entity
@Entity
public class User {
    private Long id;
    private String name;
    private String email;
    private String password;
}
DTO
public class UserDto {
    private Long id;
    private String name;
    private String email;
}
❌ Manual Mapping Example
public UserDto convertToDto(User user) {

    UserDto dto = new UserDto();

    dto.setId(user.getId());
    dto.setName(user.getName());
    dto.setEmail(user.getEmail());

    return dto;
}

And reverse mapping:

public User convertToEntity(UserDto dto) {

    User user = new User();

    user.setId(dto.getId());
    user.setName(dto.getName());
    user.setEmail(dto.getEmail());

    return user;
}
😵 Problems with Manual Mapping
1️⃣ Too Much Boilerplate Code

For every field you write:

dto.setX(entity.getX());

Imagine:

20 fields

50 entities

Hundreds of lines 😓

2️⃣ Easy to Make Mistakes

Common bugs:

dto.setEmail(user.getName()); // wrong mapping ❌

Compiler won't always catch logical errors.

3️⃣ Hard to Maintain

If you add a new field:

private String phoneNumber;

You must update mapping everywhere manually.

Miss one place → bugs.

4️⃣ Code Duplication

Same mapping logic appears in:

services

controllers

utilities

Violates DRY principle (Don't Repeat Yourself).

5️⃣ Pollutes Business Logic

Service should contain business logic:

public List<UserDto> getUsers()

But manual mapping adds clutter:

.map(user -> {
    UserDto dto = new UserDto();
    dto.setId(user.getId());
    dto.setName(user.getName());
    ...
})

Harder to read ❌

⚠️ Real Project Pain

In large enterprise apps:

Hundreds of DTOs

Nested objects

Bidirectional mappings

Manual mapping becomes a maintenance nightmare.

✅ Why Modern Projects Avoid It

Instead of manual mapping, developers use:

MapStruct ✅ (compile-time, fastest)

ModelMapper (runtime reflection)

MapStruct generates code automatically like:

dto.setId(user.getId());
dto.setName(user.getName());

…but you never write it.

