5️⃣ Create Mapper Interface
@Mapper(componentModel = "spring")
public interface UserMapper {

    UserDto toDto(User user);

    User toEntity(UserDto dto);
}

💡 MapStruct automatically generates implementation at build time.

6️⃣ Use Mapper in Service Layer
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class UserService {

    private final UserRepository repository;
    private final UserMapper mapper;

    public List<UserDto> getAllUsers() {
        return repository.findAll()
                .stream()
                .map(mapper::toDto)
                .toList();
    }
}

✅ Clean
✅ Readable
✅ No boilerplate

7️⃣ Mapping Lists Automatically
One powerful feature of MapStruct is that it can automatically map collections like:

List

Set

Collection

You don’t need to write loops manually.

🎯 Problem Without MapStruct

Manual mapping requires looping:

public List<UserDto> convert(List<User> users) {
    List<UserDto> dtos = new ArrayList<>();

    for (User user : users) {
        UserDto dto = new UserDto();
        dto.setId(user.getId());
        dto.setName(user.getName());
        dto.setEmail(user.getEmail());
        dtos.add(dto);
    }

    return dtos;
}

❌ Boilerplate code
❌ Hard to maintain

✅ MapStruct Solution
Step 1 — Single Object Mapping
@Mapper(componentModel = "spring")
public interface UserMapper {

    UserDto toDto(User user);
}
Step 2 — Add List Mapping Method
@Mapper(componentModel = "spring")
public interface UserMapper {

    UserDto toDto(User user);

    List<UserDto> toDtoList(List<User> users);
}

✅ That’s all you write.

⚙️ What MapStruct Generates Internally

MapStruct automatically creates something like:

@Override
public List<UserDto> toDtoList(List<User> users) {
    if (users == null) {
        return null;
    }

    List<UserDto> list = new ArrayList<>(users.size());

    for (User user : users) {
        list.add(toDto(user));
    }

    return list;
}

👉 It reuses your single-object mapper.

✅ Using It in Service Layer
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class UserService {

    private final UserRepository repository;
    private final UserMapper mapper;

    public List<UserDto> getAllUsers() {
        List<User> users = repository.findAll();
        return mapper.toDtoList(users);
    }
}

Clean and readable ✅

🔁 Reverse Mapping Also Works
List<User> toEntityList(List<UserDto> dtos);

MapStruct automatically handles it.

🧠 Important Rule

MapStruct can map lists automatically only if it knows how to map the single object.

Meaning:

User → UserDto   ✅ required first

Then:

List<User> → List<UserDto> ✅ automatic
📦 Supported Collections

MapStruct supports:

List<User> → List<UserDto>
Set<User> → Set<UserDto>
Collection<User> → Collection<UserDto>

No extra configuration needed.

⭐ Real Project Benefit

Repository methods usually return lists:

repository.findAll();
repository.findByStatus("ACTIVE");
repository.findByRole("ADMIN");

With MapStruct:

No loops

No stream mapping

Cleaner services

✅ Best Practice (Cleaner Style)

You can even skip defining list methods explicitly:

List<UserDto> users = repository.findAll()
        .stream()
        .map(mapper::toDto)
        .toList();

OR (preferred for large projects):

mapper.toDtoList(repository.findAll());
✅ Interview Tip

If asked:

“Does MapStruct support collection mapping?”

Answer:

“Yes, MapStruct automatically maps collections by applying the single-object mapping method to each element.”
MapStruct handles collections automatically:

List<UserDto> toDtoList(List<User> users);

No loops required.

